'''Backyard Farms''' is a [[Madison, Maine]]-based agricultural company specializing in massive greenhouses to produce vine-ripened [[tomato]]es.<ref name=year>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/31/dining/31tomato.html?ref=general&src=me&pagewanted=all |title=Giant Greenhouses Mean Flavorful Tomatoes All Year |quote=When it was built three years ago, the company’s first 24-acre greenhouse in Madison was already the largest building in Maine. This second connected greenhouse, completed last year, brought the total area under glass to some 42 acres, or roughly the size of 32 football fields. Even in the depths of winter, a million tomatoes ripen indoors to harvest each week, snipped from their vines by workers in T-shirts and shorts. ...|work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 30, 2010 |accessdate=2010-03-31 | first=Chris | last=Ladd| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100406160142/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/31/dining/31tomato.html?ref=general&src=me&pagewanted=all| archivedate= 6 April 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> It had been owned by [[Fidelity Investments#Devonshire Investors|Devonshire Investors]], a [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]]-based branch of [[Fidelity Investments]]<ref name="ms" /> but was sold in June 2017 to a Canadian produce company, Mastronardi Produce of Ontario.<ref>[https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2013/08/08/fidelity-johnson-takes-heavy-loss-his-pursuit-perfect-tomato/1K47Kxicqhrd35i5EKj2II/story.html A heaavy loss in Fidelity's pursuit of the perfect tomato. June 9, 2017]</ref>
== History == The company was started in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.backyardfarms.com/about-us/index.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303194221/http://www.backyardfarms.com/about-us/index.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2016-03-03 |title= About Us|accessdate=2010-03-31 |quote= |publisher=Backyard Farms }}</ref><ref name=year /> In 2007, the company’s first {{convert|25|acre|m2|adj=on}} greenhouse was built in [[Madison, Maine]], making it the largest building by volume in the state.<ref name=year /> It covers the area of 20 football fields. The 240,000 plants grow up to 10&nbsp;feet tall and are projected to yield 1&nbsp;million tomatoes each week.<ref name=thriving>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=25-Acre Greenhouse Thriving in Maine |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/02/01/AR2007020100419.html |quote=In Madison, the glass-covered greenhouse on a former dairy farm stretches nearly as far as the eye can see. At more than 1 million square feet, it is roughly the size of six Wal-Mart Supercenters or more than 20 football fields. With a capacity of 240,000 plants growing up to 10-feet tall, the greenhouse is projected to yield 1 million tomatoes a week. That adds up to 7,700 tons a year. And that could be only the beginning. |work=[[Associated Press]] in [[The Washington Post]] |date=February 1, 2007 |accessdate=2010-06-01 | first=Jerry | last=Harkavy}}</ref> Their second greenhouse, connected to the first, was built in 2009. The combined area was then {{convert|42|acre|m2}}.<ref name=year /> Plants are grown in [[rock wool]] and pollinated by [[bumblebee]]s that are kept inside the greenhouses.<ref name="ms">{{cite web | url=http://www.onlinesentinel.com/archive/massive-tomato-growing-operation-in-madison-is-thriving.html?pagenum=full | title=Massive tomato-growing operation in Madison is thriving | publisher=Morning Sentinel | date=March 16, 2010 | accessdate=2013-06-01 | author=Harlow, Doug | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201224734/http://www.onlinesentinel.com/archive/massive-tomato-growing-operation-in-madison-is-thriving.html?pagenum=full | archive-date=2014-02-01 | dead-url=yes | df= }}</ref> Rainwater that sheds off the greenhouse roofs is recycled to supplement the water used to irrigate the plants.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.columbiapublications.com/tomatomagazine/summer_fresh.htm | title=Summer Fresh Tomatoes Available Year-Round | publisher=COlumbia Publications | work=Tomato Magazine | date=April 2008 | accessdate=2013-06-01 | author=Vandergiessen, Arie}}</ref>
Although the tomatoes originally had been a specialty variety called "Backyard Beauty", they had been replaced with other, undisclosed varieties.<ref name="ms" /> There had been plans for the operation to expand to include peppers, eggplants, cucumbers, herbs, and strawberries.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.madisonmaine.com/index.asp?Type=B_BASIC&SEC=%7BF2D22BC6-6B4F-47A1-93BE-DA6062A8C047%7D&DE=%7B00FC43A3-5BA4-4066-A40B-EC262DA8327C%7D | title=Backyard Farms | publisher=Madison, Maine | accessdate=2013-06-01}}</ref>
