The '''EEG DIN connector''' (also referred to as '''DIN 42802''' or '''EEG safety DIN connector''') is an [[electrical connector]] used to connect [[medical]] and [[biomedical]] recording systems, such as [[electrode]]s to [[electroencephalograph]] (EEG) as used in [[neurology]]. This type of connector is the ''de facto'' standard for electromedical instruments as it was adopted by the industry under pressure from regulatory bodies (including the [[Food and Drug Administration|FDA]]) to impose insulated connectors in clinical settings for safety reasons through the [[IEC 60601]]-1 (subclause 56.3(c)) norm.

In 1989, the [[Deutsches Institut für Normung]] has issued the 42802 standard<ref>{{cite web |title=DKE Deutsche Kommission Elektrotechnik Elektronik Informationstechnik in DIN und VDE |url=https://www.din.de/de/mitwirken/normenausschuesse/dke?level=tpl-art-detailansicht&committeeid=54738887&artid=1441533&languageid=en&bcrumblevel=3 |website=www.din.de |accessdate=1 November 2018|language=German}}</ref> which specified a "touch-proof connector for electromedical application".

The EEG DIN connector mainly exist  in two types both featuring touch-proof sockets around in-line rigid plugs :
* The DIN 42802-1 connector with a 1.5&nbsp;mm diameter pin
* And the E-DIN 42802-2 with a 2&nbsp;mm diameter pin.

